<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 KLONDIKE PARK: From Seattle to Dawson City by Archie Satterfield (Fulcrum: 
$15.95; 196 pp., illustrated, paperback original). On August 16, 1896, four 
miners discovered gold in Bonanza Creek, precipitating a stampede of would-be 
prospectors into the Yukon Territory, a region geography and climate made 
virtually inaccessible. Satterfield guides the reader along the most popular 
trail, which ran from Seattle to Dawson City in the Klondike via Skagway and 
White Horse, peppering his account with colorful anecdotes. This entertaining 
history offers an introduction to the string of parks and preserves the U.S. 
and Canadian governments will open in August, 1997, along the historic route 
that lead a few to great wealth and many to great hardships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
