</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE WINTER MURDER CASE by S.S. Van Dine (Otto Penzler/Macmillan: $6.95; 174 
pp.) . Originally published in 1939, but long out of print, "The Winter Murder 
Case" was the last Philo Vance mystery. As a detective, Vance resembles the 
suave Nick Charles, rather than the hard-boiled Sam Spade: He smokes Regie 
cigarettes and seems at home in the posh household of the millionaire-emerald 
collector Carrington Rexxon. "Winter Murder" remains a diverting yarn, 55 years 
after its initial appearance, and aspiring crime writers should study Van 
Dine's no-nonsense afterward, "Twenty Rules For Writing Detective Stories." 
</P>
</TEXT>
