<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: ALHAMBRA; PLAN FOR SMITH'S REVIVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A plan has been revived to convert part of the city's old Sears store site at 
Fremont and Commonwealth avenues to a Smith's Food & Drug Center. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members, sitting as the Alhambra Redevelopment Agency board, have 
approved an agreement with Smith's Food & Drug Center Inc. for the Salt Lake 
City firm to build a supermarket up to 66,600 square feet next to the 
unoccupied Sears. 
</P>
<P>
 In the fall, Smith's called off plans to demolish the Sears store and build on 
its site. Sears closed April 3. 
</P>
<P>
 The council also agreed to purchase the Sears building and some land next to 
it from Haagen Alhambra Retail. This land would be combined with a city-owned 
parking lot on one side of Sears as the site for Smith's. 
</P>
<P>
 Michael Martin, deputy director of the agency, said the deal would cost the 
agency about $325,000 and leave it as owner of the empty Sears store. The city 
would pay an estimated $5.25 million for the Sears property and sell a portion 
to Smith's, a food and drug chain, for approximately $4.9 million, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
