<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS, TIPS & BARGAINS; THE PRIVATE LIFE OF NOEL COWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Twenty years after Noel Coward's death, the four-acre Jamaican estate where 
the playwright entertained the likes of Laurence Olivier, Claudette Colbert, 
David Niven, the Queen Mother and Winston Churchill is aglow once again. 
</P>
<P>
 "Firefly," named because of the prevalence of lightning bugs, has been 
reopened in the town of Port Maria, near Oracabessa. Visitors may tour the 
painstakingly restored house and grounds, watch a 20-minute video on Coward's 
life and career, and ogle the fine collection of memorabilia. Admission is $10. 
Information: Jamaica Tourist Board, (213) 384-1123. 
</P>
