<HEADLINE>
<P>
AN ADDED PERSPECTIVE ON THE VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 You may have noticed that the title of this page changed three weeks ago, From 
"Valley Editorials" to "Valley Perspective." We're taking a moment to explain 
why. 
</P>
<P>
 Since April, The Times has produced a separate page of editorials on Sundays 
devoted to matters of interest to the San Fernando, Antelope and Santa Clarita 
valleys, and Glendale. But events often require immediate attention, such as 
the first reports, in November, of a serial child molester at large in the San 
Fernando Valley. The Times' first editorial on those crimes appeared on the 
following day, a Wednesday, and ran in every edition of the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
 On many occasions, the news that happens here is mirrored by events in other 
parts of Los Angeles or Southern California as a whole. At such times, an 
editorial addressing the problem of graffiti vandalism, for example, might 
highlight solutions that have worked here or in other parts of the state or the 
nation. Those Valley-area editorials frequently appear during the week, on The 
Times' main editorial page. 
</P>
<P>
 Times Valley Edition readers will now find it easier to locate these weekday 
editorials on matters of importance to them. They will be highlighted by the 
headline "Valley Perspective." To prevent confusion, the Sunday Valley Edition 
editorial page now carries the same name. 
</P>
<P>
 It's another sign of our belief that the valleys and their environs have 
evolved into far more complex and diverse localities that are deserving of more 
attention, opinion, debate and comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
