<HEADLINE>
<P>
MCA EFFORT TO RELOCATE PROPOSED RAIL STATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * A recent letter writer (Dec. 12) takes MCA to task for supporting a new 
alternative location for the Universal City subway station. 
</P>
<P>
 Sure, MCA would be happy if this new location were approved.And so too, would 
the hundreds of small retailers and other small businesses located in the 
Universal City area who would benefit from the commuters and tourists using the 
subway station. 
</P>
<P>
 Local residents would benefit as well. There will be relief from added traffic 
congestion along Lankershim Boulevard if the station is built on the new site. 
And commuters coming and going will be able to park right next to the subway 
station, instead of in lots that are inconvenient and far removed. 
</P>
<P>
 The new location would benefit virtually everyone. Lets hope the MTA makes the 
wisest decision and gives a "thumbs up" to this site. 
</P>
<P>
 JAMES M. MAHFET 
</P>
<P>
 North Hollywood 
</P>
<P>
 Mahfet is executive vice president of the Universal City-North Hollywood 
Chamber of Commerce.  
</P>
<P>
 * I have just read about Universal Studios' request that a subway station 
proposed for the area around Lankershim and Ventura boulevards be located at 
its CityWalk attraction (Sept. 30). 
</P>
<P>
 Asking the tired workers to climb the hill to the studios is about as 
thoughtless as you can get. Yes, I think it would help their business on the 
hill, but is that the focus of the city's attention, or is it for the workers 
who must make this trip every day, unlike tourists at CityWalk? 
</P>
<P>
 I hope the entire Valley supports resistance to this suggestion.  
</P>
<P>
 J.A. LA HIVE 
</P>
<P>
 Studio City 
</P>
