<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: WORLD SWIM MARK SET BY RUSSIA'S POPOV 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Olympic champion Alexandre Popov of Russia set a world record of 47.83 seconds 
in the 100-meter freestyle event at the World Cup Short Course swimming 
competition Saturday in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
 The former record of 47.94 seconds was set by Brazilian Gustavo Borges on July 
2, 1993. Short-course records can be set only in 25-meter pools. 
</P>
<P>
 Popov won the 50-meter and 100-meter freestyle events at the Barcelona 
Olympics. Pro Basketball  
</P>
<P>
 Dikembe Mutombo's play before his ejection from Thursday's Denver-Golden State 
game will be reviewed by the NBA. Mutombo was called for a flagrant foul for 
elbowing Warrior forward Chris Webber and later received a technical foul for 
taunting Warrior center Chris Gatling. 
</P>
<P>
 The Charlotte Hornets signed free agent Lorenzo Williams to fill in for the 
injured Larry Johnson. College Football  
</P>
<P>
 Two were killed and seven others were when their vehicle careened out of 
control on the way from the Independence Bowl in Shreveport, La., to New 
Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
 Killed were Charles Edison Brewer III of Shreveport and Scott David Miller of 
Ft. Worth, both 22. 
</P>
<P>
 The driver, Matthew Carter, 25, of Shreveport, ran off the left side of the 
road Friday night and lost control when he tried to get back off the median, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
 The utility vehicle flipped four or five times, throwing out all nine 
occupants, two containers of beer and some liquor bottles. 
</P>
<P>
 Ty Scroggins, a 220-pound junior linebacker, was charged with first-degree 
assault and released on $5,000 bond Saturday, becoming the third Louisville 
player charged after a Christmas Eve incident at a Louisville, Ky., nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
 During the incident, a 23-year-old man allegedly was beaten and a 23-year-old 
woman was assaulted. Names in the News  
</P>
<P>
 Two-time world champion Espen Bredesen of Norway won a World Cup ski-jumping 
event at Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany, with a jump of 364 feet. . . . 
Geoffrey Abrams of Newport Beach beat Sebastian Gobbi of France, 6-3, 6-4, to 
win the boys' 16 title at the Port Washington (N.Y.) International 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
 World 10,000-meter champion Haile Gebresilassie won the New Year's Day World 
Cross-Country Challenge at Beamish, England. Paula Radcliffe won the women's 
race. . . . Canada beat the United States, 8-3, at the world junior hockey 
championships at Frydek-Mistek, Czech Republic. 
</P>
