<HEADLINE>
<P>
'93/'94 YEAR-END REVIEW AND OUTLOOK; INDUSTRY OUTLOOK; CONTINUING LOW-GRADE 
GROWTH IN THE NATIONAL ECONOMY, COUPLED WITH HOPES FOR STABILITY -- IF NOT 
EXPANSION -- IN CALIFORNIA, IS THE BACKDROP FOR THE YEAR IN BUSINESS. HERE IS 
AN ASSESSMENT OF KEY INDUSTRIES' PROSPECTS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS KRAUL, This report was compiled by Times staff writer Donna K.H. 
Walters. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BANKING: California banks' problem loans finally have begun abating, and the 
industry is poised for profit growth after years of consolidation and cost 
cutting. Lenders still suffer from borrowers' reluctance and the region's 
relative unattractiveness to new employers. CHRIS KRAUL 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010294-0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 000519 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 2, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 3; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
42 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'93/'94 YEAR-END REVIEW AND OUTLOOK; INDUSTRY OUTLOOK; CONTINUING LOW-GRADE 
GROWTH IN THE NATIONAL ECONOMY, COUPLED WITH HOPES FOR STABILITY -- IF NOT 
EXPANSION -- IN CALIFORNIA, IS THE BACKDROP FOR THE YEAR IN BUSINESS. HERE IS 
AN ASSESSMENT OF KEY INDUSTRIES' PROSPECTS. 
</P>
